    44	This paper does so in the unit health economists use to compare a death averted against years
    45	lived in better health: the quality-adjusted life-year. The exercise is deliberately in the style
    46	of a charity evaluator’s cost-effectiveness analysis (GiveWell 2026), scaled from a program to a
    47	portfolio, with one addition the setting forces: because most of the portfolio funds interventions
    48	whose health effects have never been causally measured, the model makes its epistemics explicit.
    49	Every effect is shrunk toward zero in proportion to how well its supporting study identifies
    50	causation, the shrinkage schedule is a slider rather than a buried constant, and the headline
    51	is reported across the full range of evidence philosophies — from counting only randomized
    52	evidence to taking every published estimate at face value.
    53	The paper makes four contributions. It provides what I believe is the first outside, portfolio-level
    54	cost-effectiveness estimate of an individual mega-donor’s disclosed lifetime giving — funder-run
    55	portfolio metrics exist, including GiveWell’s aggregate impact estimates (GiveWell 2026), Robin
    56	Hood’s benefit–cost framework (Robin Hood Foundation 2025), the Constellation Fund’s portfolio
    57	reporting (Constellation Fund 2025), and social-rate-of-return analysis of USAID’s Development
    58	Innovation Ventures portfolio (Center for Effective Global Action 2023); the difference here is
    59	independence from the donor, a subject who publishes no outcome data, and explicit evidence
    60	weighting: a best-guess median of 202,000 QALYs from $26.39 billion nominal ($30.3B in
