   147	Each Monte Carlo draw allocates the giving across archetypes (a Dirichlet centered on the
   148	derived shares), assigns each archetype a cost per QALY drawn from a distribution anchored in
   149	published estimates, and multiplies the implied QALYs by two independent discounts. Causal
   150	credibility asks whether the measured effect is real. Each archetype carries the identification
   151	tier of its best supporting evidence, and the tier sets a Beta-distributed shrinkage factor toward
   152	the null: a lottery-randomized wealth shock (Cesarini et al. 2016) or the Medicaid mortality
   153	quasi-experiments — the ACA expansions (Miller et al. 2021), with cost–benefit arithmetic
   154	from the pre-ACA state expansions (Sommers 2017) whose spending component draws on the
   155	Oregon Health Insurance Experiment (Finkelstein et al. 2012) — keeps most of its effect;
   156	replicated child-targeted cash quasi-experiments (Aizer et al. 2016) anchor the cash bucket;
   157	the community-health-center rollout design (Bailey and Goodman-Bacon 2015) and similar
   158	contested quasi-experiments keep less; associational and assumption-only categories are shrunk
   159	near zero. Realization asks whether a marginal philanthropic dollar delivers the studied effect at
   160	all — transport to different populations, overhead, and funging, net of possible capacity effects:
   161	surveyed Scott recipients report stronger capacity and reach (Buteau et al. 2023), self-reports
   162	on whose basis the model permits realization above one (an author judgment, not a CEP effect
   163	estimate). It is one global triangular draw with mode 0.80 on support 0.55–1.10.
   164	The two multipliers are designed to partition the doubt — transportability concerns in realization,
   165	identification concerns in credibility, cost-per-QALY priors stated conditional on the effect being
